4.1 Data Acquisition

4.2 Attributes

Groundwater Depth

ggplot(gw_depth, aes(x = Date, y = water_depth)) + 
  geom_line(color = 'slateblue2') + 
  ylab('Ground Water Depth (feet)') +
  theme_bw()

Figure 4.1: Groundwater depth for water years 1992 through 2022 at a ground water site near Mammoth Lakes. 

ggplotly(gw_depth %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = water_depth)) + 
  geom_line(color = 'slateblue2'))

Figure 4.1: Groundwater depth for water years 1992 through 2022 at a ground water site near Mammoth Lakes.

Groundwater depths near Mammoth Lakes, California have been progressively getting deeper since 1992. The graph shows the greatest trending decline was between 2000 and 2003. There is one trend after 2006 that shows an increase in the water table but after that spike in ground water recharge the depth goes down again significantly. Overall there is a positive relationship between ground water depths and time.

Surface Discharge

ggplot(q_ca, aes(x = Date, y = q_cfs)) + 
  geom_line(color = 'paleturquoise') + 
  ylab('Q (cfs)') +
  theme_bw()

Figure 4.2: Represented above is the daily annual discharge showing the rates for water years between 1992 to 2022. 

ggplotly(q_ca %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = q_cfs)) + 
  geom_line(color = 'paleturquoise'))

Figure 4.2: Represented above is the daily annual discharge showing the rates for water years between 1992 to 2022.

Discharge is influenced by many outside sources. The outputs along Hot Creek range from 30 cubic feet per second (cfs) to a little over 300 cfs. With the exception of the occasional spikes around 300 cfs the river shows a decreasing trend in annual ranges of discharge.

4.3 Attribute Analysis

GW and SW Long

sw_gw <- left_join(gw_depth, q_ca, by = "Date")

sw_gw_graph <- ggplot() +
    geom_line(data = sw_gw, aes(x=Date, y=water_depth*3), color = 'slateblue2') +  
    geom_line(data = sw_gw, aes(x=Date, y=q_cfs), color = 'paleturquoise') 

sw_gw_graph + scale_y_continuous(name = "Dicharge (cfs)" , sec.axis = sec_axis(trans=~./3 , name= "Groundwater Depth (feet)")) +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("Date")

Figure 4.3: Here a logistical comparison of groundwater and surface water discharge trends are shown for water years 1992 to 2022.

Comparing ground water depths and surface water discharge rates can help show how surface water can be affected by ground water levels. The double y-axis allows the two variable to be compared by annual averages. The two variables are on different scales but a small correlation can be seen between increasing water table levels and discharge peaks.

Temperature and Precipitation

t_annual <- mam_climate %>%
  dplyr::mutate(month = month(Date),
                year = year(Date)) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarize(Avrg_T = mean(Avrg_T, na.rm = T)) 

p_annual <- mam_climate %>%
  dplyr::mutate(month = month(Date),
                year = year(Date)) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarize(Precip = mean(Precip, na.rm = T))

t_p_annual <- cbind(t_annual, p_annual) %>%
  select(-3)

t_p <- ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = t_p_annual, aes(x=year, y= Avrg_T), color = 'lightsalmon3', size= 1.2) +
  geom_line(data = t_p_annual, aes(x=year, y=Precip*10), color = 'darkslategray2', size= 1.2)+
  xlab("Water Year") +
  scale_color_brewer(guide = "legend")

t_p + scale_y_continuous(name = "Temp (F)" , sec.axis = sec_axis(trans=~./10 , name= "Precip (mm)")) +
  theme_bw()

Figure 4.4: Above shows the comparison between temperature and precipitation. The data is the same time frame as the ground water and surfacewater data starting in 1992 to 2022.

This graph compares the trends of temperature and precipitation over the studied time frame. The temperature has a consistent pattern with no major spikes in either decreasing or increasing temperatures, however it can be noted that there is a general upward trend in the temperature data. Precipitation is much more variable and has significant ranges over the years. Looking at the graph some correlation between the two variables can be seen where there is a dip in temperature precipitation shows a rise and when there is an increase in temperature there is a significant decrease in precipitation such as the section of data between 2010 and 2015.

GW, Temp, Precip

gw_annual <- gw_depth %>%
  dplyr::mutate(month = month(Date),
                year = year(Date)) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarize(water_depth = mean(water_depth, na.rm = T)) 

gw_tp_annual <- left_join(gw_annual, t_p_annual)

layout(matrix(c(1,2), 1, 2, byrow = TRUE)) +
plot(gw_tp_annual$water_depth, gw_tp_annual$Avrg_T, col="lightsalmon3", pch = 16, main="Temperature", ylab = "Average Temperature (F)", xlab = "Water Depth (ft)") +
plot(gw_tp_annual$water_depth, gw_tp_annual$Precip, col="darkslategray2", pch = 16, main="Precipitation", xlab = "Water Depth (ft)", ylab = "Precipitation (mm)")

Figure 4.5: Ground water levels compared to temperature and precipitation climate variables. 

## integer(0)

Ground water recharge is dependent on many factors but two climate variable that can influence ground water depth is temperature and precipitation. Comparing the two variable against the water table level allows for a relationship to be interpreted. Based on the graphs there is allegedly a positive trend between temperature and ground water with some outlying points. Water depth is shown to be increasing as temperature also increases. Precipitation and ground water do not show any distinct trends from the graph so a statistical analysis will be needed to better understand the relation. The extreme points on the precipitation graph do show some assumptions of when there is high amounts of precipitation the ground water depth is less and when there is minimal precipitation the water table depth tends to be deeper.

Monthly Water Trends

Discharge Trends for baseflow months

q_base <- q_month_means %>% 
  filter(month %in% c('7','8','9','10'))

ggplot(q_base, aes( x= year, y= q_mean)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(month))) +
  scale_y_log10() +
  ylab('Q (cfs)') +
  xlab('Water Year')+
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Month", labels = c("July", "August", "September", "October"))

Figure 4.6: Baseflow is represented by the months between July and October. Here the diffrence between monthly discharge is shown.

Baseflow discharge rates are generally supported by ground water sources. The graph shows a typical monthly trend where surface water discharges decreases in months further away from snow melt and summer rain storms. The latest month of October never surpasses 70 cfs but July has an extremely wide range of discharge values over the study period. Overall the earlier months have higher discharge values than the later months. Some years there are significant differences between each of the months such as the data from around 1995 and other years there is a minimal change in discharge between the baseflow months such as the data around 2020.

Groundwater Baseflow Months

gw_month <- gw_depth %>%
  dplyr::mutate(month = month(Date),
                year = year(Date)) %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarize(water_depth = mean(water_depth, na.rm = T)) 


gw_base <- gw_month %>% 
  filter(month %in% c('7','8','9','10'))

ggplot(gw_base, aes( x= year, y= water_depth)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(month))) +
  scale_y_log10() +
  ylab('Groundwater Depth (feet)') +
  xlab('Water Year')+
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Month", labels = c("July", "August", "September", "October"))

To compare groundwater with discharge during baseflow months the averages for groundwater for the months of July - October are shown.Throughout the years in this study it is seen that groundwater during baseflow months has progressivley been getting deeper.

Groundwater and Q in October

gw_10 <- gw_base %>%
  filter(month %in% ('10'))

q_10 <- q_base %>%
  filter(month %in% ('10'))


gw_q <- left_join(gw_10, q_10)

ggplot(gw_q, aes(x= q_mean, y= water_depth, color = year)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x= 'Q (cfs)', y= 'Groundwater (ft)') +
  scale_color_continuous() +
  theme_bw()

From the baseflow months it seems there were correlations between grounDwater and discharge particularly in the month of October. On the ground water versus discharge graph for October it is noticeable that water tables closer to the surface result in greater discharge values and as groundwater gets deeper the discharge decreases. In this graph it also shows the trend that over the years it is more common to see deeper water tables and less discharge in the Hot Creek stream.

t_test <- gw_tp_annual %>%
  select(-Precip)

test <- t_test %>%
  filter(year <2018)

mk.test(log10(test$Avrg_T))
## 
##  Mann-Kendall trend test
## 
## data:  log10(test$Avrg_T)
## z = 1.1902, n = 26, p-value = 0.234
## alternative hypothesis: true S is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##            S         varS          tau 
##   55.0000000 2058.3333333    0.1692308
sens.slope(test$Avrg_T)
## 
##  Sen's slope
## 
## data:  test$Avrg_T
## z = 1.1902, n = 26, p-value = 0.234
## alternative hypothesis: true z is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.0230378  0.1201857
## sample estimates:
## Sen's slope 
##  0.04791318
#not signigicant change of increasing temp by 0.05 degrees each year

Using a non-parametric statistical test such as the Mann-Kendall showed which variables were significantly changing and then using the Sen’s Slope test identified what type of trend the parameter was experiencing. For the analysis parameters tested included surface water monthly averages and baseflow (July-October) monthly averages from 1992 to 2022. Also tested was groundwater depth trends and temperature for the same time period 1992 to 2022. After running the tests it was found that monthly surface water discharge rates were significant with a p-value of 1.1e-07 and a slope of -0.038. Baseflow months also had a significant p-value of 5.3e-05 with a negative trending slope of -0.19. The tests on groundwater levels were significant but to a minuscule degree. The p-value was less than 2.2e-16 with a positive slope of 0.00028. Temperature was the only parameter to give insignificant results with a p-value of 0.23 and a slope of 0.048.
